    "faq_section_t9pdQ3": {
      "type": "faq-section",
      "blocks": {
        "faq_item_GXVkDi": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "When should you upgrade an engagement ring?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>There’s no fixed timeline. Most couples upgrade their engagement ring during milestone moments like anniversaries, promotions, new beginnings, or personal achievements. Some upgrade when their lifestyle changes, when their taste changes, or simply when they feel ready for a design that reflects who they are now</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_pKazQL": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "What is the meaning of ring upgrade?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>A ring upgrade simply means improving or changing your current engagement ring. It could involve increasing the diamond size, changing the setting, switching metals, or redesigning the entire piece. It’s a practical way to refresh your ring so it matches your taste, lifestyle, or budget today. The meaning is personal, for many, it’s a way to keep the ring relevant and wearable long-term.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_zc6Aem": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "What should I do with my old engagement ring?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>You can repurpose the diamond into a new setting, turn it into a pendant, redesign it into a different style, or keep it aside as family heirloom. Some people use the diamond in a stacking band or a special occasion ring. If the metal is worn or outdated, it can be traded in or melted down for a new piece</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_EJx4R9": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "How are diamonds graded for quality",
            "faq_answer": "<p>Diamonds are graded using the Four Cs: cut, color, clarity and carat. Cut affects sparkle, color measures whiteness, clarity looks at natural marks and carat refers to weight and size. These four factors determine a diamond’s overall quality and price. Both natural and lab grown diamonds follow the same grading standards, which makes comparing options easier when upgrading.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_QC3YVe": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "What damages engagement rings?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>Chemicals, chlorine, lotions, hard impacts and daily wear can damage an engagement ring. Prongs may loosen, stones can become dull and metal can wear down over time. Activities like gym workouts, swimming and cleaning are common causes. Regular cleaning and inspections help prevent long term issues and keep the ring secure and shining.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_hFdTbQ": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "What are the 4 qualities of a diamond?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>The four qualities of a diamond are cut, color, clarity, and carat, known as the Four Cs. Cut influences brilliance, color measures tint, clarity checks for imperfections, and carat indicates size. These characteristics help determine the value and appearance of the diamond and are essential to understand when upgrading or redesigning a ring.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
